INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("285", "2", "2014-02-10 21:32:54", "2014-02-10 21:32:54", "Turkey may not be historys original tea drinkers, but they have made up for the late start with an amazing amount of consumption over the last 100 or so years. The particular type of tea, method of brewing and even how it is consumed is uniquely Turkeys own creation. Within the country of Turkey black tea is one of the most popular beverages, second only to water. It is also a popular way to show hospitality to guests and a common social drink. It is so popular there is even a folk saying in Turkey which when translated states, Conversations without tea are like a night sky without the moon.\r\n<h2>History of Turkish Tea</h2>\r\nTea was traded throughout Turkey for centuries before it became commonly consumed. It was not until the 1880s that the health benefits of tea began to be touted publicly. Thus ensued its slow progression towards popularity. The 1950s saw the growth of tea gardens, and the social benefits of sitting over a cup of tea began to be appreciated. Efforts to grow tea on Turkish soil were extensive and resulted in many falters and failures. They persisted, however, and today it is one of their largest crops. In fact they are currently now one of the largest tea producers in the world. Turkish tea is grown today along the coast near the Black Sea.\r\n<h2>How Turkish Tea is Prepared &amp; Served</h2>\r\nTurkish tea is brewed in a special type of pot called a caydanlik, which is actually two pots stacked together. The bottom, larger pot boils water, while the top is used to steep the tea leaves. Once the water has begun to boil, several spoonsful of water is transferred from the bottom pot to the top. The leaves are left to steep while the heated water below keeps everything hot.\r\nWhen it is time to serve, the table is not set with tea cups. Special clear, curved glasses are used. This allows the drinker to appreciate the color of the tea. Milk or cream are never used with Turkish tea, but a little sugar is acceptable.\r\nThe tea is poured into the small glasses. At this point it is quite concentrated in flavor, so water from the bottom kettle is added to make it a little more diluted. The tea is very strong so filling it half with the tea and the remained the hot water is typical. The glasses will be exceptionally hot, so must be held by the top rim only.\r\n<h2>Turkish Teas Role in Turkish Culture</h2>\r\nTea is enjoyed from morning to evening in Turkey. It is also consumed at home as well as at coffeehouses throughout the country. It is a social drink and a method of showing hospitality. It is considered rude for any host to not allow their guest to drink as much of the popular beverage as they like.", "A Guide to Turkish Tea", "", "trash", "open", "open", "", "guide-turkish-tea", "", "", "2014-03-18 00:58:53", "2014-03-18 00:58:53", "", "0", "http://midtown.pera.wpengine.com/?p=285", "0", "post", "", "0");
