INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("946", "2", "2013-07-11 20:23:56", "2013-07-11 20:23:56", "<p dir=\"ltr\">When starting to research your next travel adventure, you want a place to get information from a real person.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Someone who has been to the places you want to see and experienced the things you want to experience.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The blogs below are good resources for information and colorful stories of the writers own adventures.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1. <a href=\"http://turkishtravelblog.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Turkish Travel Blog</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you want a blog that gives you not only information about places to visit and things to see but also food you must eat and traditions you should witness or can participate in, check out turkishtravelblog.com. Natalie is originally from the UK and moved to Turkey and now has a goal of seeing everything and going everywhere the country has to offer. Its a tall order but shes up for it!</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. <a href=\"http://turkeytravelblog.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Turkey Travel Blog</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This blog is a little more technical and informational. It offers how-tos and suggested companies to use for certain things from tours to travel arrangements. With a focus on the larger cities, this is a good start if youre planning your first trip to Turkey and want to do the standard, tourist based things.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3. <a href=\"http://www.mytravelingjoys.com/\" target=\"_blank\">My Traveling Joys</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This blog includes travels from Turkey, Poland, and other places both domestic and international. The blog writer, Joy, is a pastry chef and focuses on food in many of her articles.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">4. <a href=\"http://www.travellerspoint.com/blogs/Turkey/\" target=\"_blank\">Travellerspoint - Turkey</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Travellerspoint is a great resource for posts by many people and many things sorted by country. Not only does it give peoples perceptions of the places they visit but also talks about important topics while traveling. These posts include traveling alone as a woman, customs in the country youre going to, and how to handle medical emergencies in the country youre visiting.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">5. <a href=\"http://istanbuleats.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Istanbul Eats</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Food, food, food, and more food! If youre going to find yourself in Istanbul and consider yourself a foodie, this is the blog for you! Not only does this site include reviews and restaurant suggestions, there is also a section to find authentic Turkish recipes to try at home!</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">6. <a href=\"http://www.theturkishlife.com/\" target=\"_blank\">The Turkish Life</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An American woman who moved from San Francisco to Istanbul updates this blog about her life in the city. This is a more down-to-earth blog, which includes commentary on local news and political unrest and is a helpful perspective on life in Turkey.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">7. <a href=\"http://turkishculturalfoundation.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Turkish Cultural Foundation</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Turkish Cultural Foundation maintains this useful and informative website. There are portals for cuisine, music, culture, and connecting with people. If you want to brush up on your cultural references, works of art, or find a connection in Turkey this is a great resource.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">8. <a href=\"http://www.istanbultrails.com/\">Istanbul Trails</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An all-inclusive take on traveling to Istanbul, a man who has lived in Turkey for nearly 10 years writes this blog. Many articles are sorted into the categories on the left hand side of the page in useful groupings like Things To See &amp; Do, Transportation, and his Tips &amp; Tricks. This site is highly recommended for an easy to navigate layout and organized information.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">9. <a href=\"http://turkeywithstuffin.wordpress.com/\">Turkeywithstuffins Blog</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Beyond the clever name, this blog is witty and humorous. A British woman who has married a Turkish real estate agent and shares her stories about her in-laws and living in Turkey writes it. Not everything she writes is about Turkey but the entries that are offer great insight into living in this unique country. Reading good English humor will never get old.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">10. <a href=\"http://www.turkeytravelcentre.com/blog/\">Turkey Travel Blog by Turkey Travel Centre</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This blog is written by a team of experts that have traveled extensively in Turkey for a number of years. Their primary purpose is to sell tours, which are all offered with information and a good rating on Trip Advisor, but their blog has unique topics that would interest anyone traveling to Turkey.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Enjoy researching your trip to Turkey and after youve visited, maybe youll get inspired to start your own blog! Bon voyage!</p>\n\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"></div>", "10 Good Turkish Travel Blogs", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "10-good-turkish-travel-blogs", "", "", "2013-07-11 20:23:56", "2013-07-11 20:23:56", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=946", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("958", "2", "2013-07-18 15:33:01", "2013-07-18 15:33:01", "Turkey offers amazing activities that include sightseeing, beach activities, and museums.Each of these promises an amazing experience.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Turkey presents a great climate for visiting, but there are a few times of the year when it is best to plan your visit.</p>\nTurkey has seven distinct regions all with varying weather climates. It can be tricky to pack all the right clothes for your trip if youre spending time in multiple regions.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Whether youre out to lounge on the beach for your vacation, tour the museums and hike the famous trails, or just spend time in the big cities, knowing what to expect from Mother Nature may make or break your Turkish adventure.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Planning Your Beach Trip To Turkey</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"200\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Amasra_1260452_nevit.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Photographs from Amasra\" alt=\"Photographs from Amasra\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Amasra_1260452_nevit.jpg/300px-Amasra_1260452_nevit.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a> Amasra[/caption]\n\nIf youre looking at spending most of your time in the water and in the beach towns, plan your trip for mid-May through September. The air outside may be hot, but the water will be cool and perfect for swimming, surfing, kayaking, and most other water sports you want to try.\n\nSince most people visit Turkey for the museums and bigger city tourist locations, you may be able to find pockets of cheaper rates and shorter lines (depending on destination) during the summer season, as it is too hot for many visitors.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Visiting Museums, Bazaars and Other Destinations In Turkey</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/44068917@N00/4118471718\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Grand Bazaar, Istanbul, Turkey (Nov 2009)\" alt=\"Grand Bazaar, Istanbul, Turkey (Nov 2009)\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2508/4118471718_f057d78345_m.jpg\" width=\"150\" /></a> Grand Bazaar, Istanbul[/caption]\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If relaxing on the beach and water activities aren\'t your thingand you want to spend time in the museums, bazaars, and hiking in the countryside, try to plan your trip either in the spring (April and May) or the autumn (September and October).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Spring is the best time to visit as all the leaves are turning green and nearly everything is blooming. If your target location is along the Black Sea, shoot for April or September when the weather is the best and the tourists are at their lower points but it is still in season.</p>\nEarly in the season is best for these locations if you dont plan on spending all your time in the water but still want to enjoy the beach and the view. The old adage is true- April showers bring May flowers. If you travel to Turkey in April, bring your rain gear. While it may not be torrential rain, you will likely experience some rainy days and you dont want them to put a damper on your adventures!\n\nBug spray is vital if youre visiting in the summer months, between June and August.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Traveling To Turkey In Winter</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The one time of year that may not be ideal to visit Turkeyis winter especially if you plan on visiting the central part of the country.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Road closures, snowstorms, and tourist locations being shut down for the season make for a rather uninviting vacation spot.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many locations are closed between mid-October and April, but Istanbul has tourist and visitor attractions available year-round. Ensure you do research on the specific places you want to visit. They may be closed for the season leading to disappointment, but if youre looking for fun in the winter Turkey can still be a great place to visit.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Check out travel blogs and other travel resources if you dont know what you want to see.</p>\nIf you can plan your ideal trip at the ideal time, you may never want to leave Turkey! Safe travels!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=f54db894-5238-43d2-9ce1-7e9010e05d64\" /></a></div>", "The Best Time to Visit Turkey", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "the-best-time-to-visit-turkey", "", "", "2013-07-18 15:33:01", "2013-07-18 15:33:01", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=958", "0", "post", "", "0");
