INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("1358", "2", "2013-12-09 16:45:01", "2013-12-09 16:45:01", "<h1></h1>\n<div>\n\nTurkish coffee is a traditional way of preparing coffee that dates back to the 1500s. It\'s still popular in many countries today, and it can be enjoyed no matter where you live. Let\'s explore some of the history behind Turkish coffee, as well as the proper way to prepare it.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>The History of Turkish Coffee</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\nFirst of all, the term Turkish when used in reference to coffee describes the method of preparing coffee, not the coffee beans themselves. While it\'s best to use a high quality and flavorful coffee bean, what really makes the beverage Turkish is how it\'s made.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCoffee first became popular in the Middle East around the 15th Century. The first recorded coffeehouse of Istanbul was opened in approximately 1555 and the phenomenon of Turkish coffee began to spread throughout the very powerful Ottoman Empire. Coffee was briefly banned for its stimulating effect, but this was soon overturned due to the beverage\'s widespread popularity.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCoffee gradually spread to the Balkans, Italy and then the rest of Europe. Different methods of preparing coffee became common in various countries, but the Turkish tradition has remained intact in most Middle Eastern and Balkan regions. Today, this way of preparing coffee is known by many different names. Arabic, Greek, Armenian and Bosnian coffee are really the same thing as Turkish coffee. The name was changed for nationalistic purposes, but the method of preparation is identical.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>How Turkish Coffee is Prepared</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cofee1.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"English: &quot;Turkish&quot; coffee in the Ara...\" alt=\"English: &quot;Turkish&quot; coffee in the Ara...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1e/Cofee1.jpg/300px-Cofee1.jpg\" width=\"210\" height=\"298\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAs mentioned, you don\'t need a specific coffee bean to make Turkish coffee, but it\'s best to use medium-roasted beans of good quality. The fresher the better. This means you should prepare the coffee soon after grinding it.\n\nThe most important fact to know about preparing Turkish coffee is that the beans must be ground extremely finely. In order to be sure to get the proper consistency, it\'s advisable to use a Turkish coffee press. Another option is to use a mortar and pestle.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAnother item that is needed for this process is called an ibrik, which is used to brew the coffee. This is a distinctive looking metal pot, usually made of copper, with a long handle. Ibriks come in various sizes, depending on how many cups of coffee you want to brew at one time.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSugar is often mixed with the coffee, as Turkish coffee is traditionally served strong but also sweet. Sometimes flavorings such as cardamon or anise are also added. Turkish coffee is brewed at a hot but not boiling\n\ntemperature. If the water is too hot, it causes the coffee to have a burnt taste.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Turkish Coffee Continues to be Popular</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\nEven though Turkish coffee is a traditional beverage with a long history, it\'s popularity continues in modern times. People seeking an alternative to Starbucks and other mainstream coffee shops may want to learn how to prepare Turkish coffee at home. Other than that, it can be found in many Turkish and other ethnic restaurants and, of course, by traveling to the countries where this style of coffee is enjoyed.\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=bf31a4ad-fa20-47de-aaf1-1b27fa24789f\" /></a></div>", "A Guide To Turkish Coffee", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "a-guide-to-turkish-coffee", "", "", "2013-12-09 16:45:01", "2013-12-09 16:45:01", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1358", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("1370", "2", "2013-12-09 16:57:43", "2013-12-09 16:57:43", "<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" style=\"width: 250px\"><dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"></dt></dl>&nbsp;\n<div>\n\nTurkey may not be history\'s original tea drinkers, but they have made up for the late start with an amazing amount of consumption over the last 100 or so years. The particular type of tea, method of brewing and even how it is consumed is uniquely Turkey\'s own creation. Within the country of Turkey black tea is one of the most popular beverages, second only to water. It is also a popular way to show hospitality to guests and a common social drink. It is so popular there is even a folk saying in Turkey which when translated states, \"Conversations without tea are like a night sky without the moon\".\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>History of Turkish Tea</h2>\nTea was traded throughout Turkey for centuries before it became commonly consumed. It was not until the 1880s that the health benefits of tea began to be touted publicly. Thus ensued its slow progression towards popularity. The 1950s saw the growth of tea gardens, and the social benefits of sitting over a cup of tea began to be appreciated. Efforts to grow tea on Turkish soil were extensive and resulted in many falters and failures. They persisted, however, and today it is one of their largest crops. In fact they are currently now one of the largest tea producers in the world. Turkish tea is grown today along the coast near the Black Sea.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2></h2>\n<h2>How Turkish Tea is Prepared &amp; Served</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/53326337@N00/4951162390\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Double-decker teapot\" alt=\"Double-decker teapot\" src=\"http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4116/4951162390_1530e94042_m.jpg\" width=\"160\" height=\"240\" /></a>\n\nTurkish tea is brewed in a special type of pot called a caydanlik, which is actually two pots stacked together. The bottom, larger pot boils water, while the top is used to steep the tea leaves. Once the water has begun to boil, several spoonsful of water is transferred from the bottom pot to the top. The leaves are left to steep while the heated water below keeps everything hot.\nWhen it is time to serve, the table is not set with tea cups. Special clear, curved glasses are used. This allows the drinker to appreciate the color of the tea. Milk or cream are never used with Turkish tea, but a little sugar is acceptable.\nThe tea is poured into the small glasses. At this point it is quite concentrated in flavor, so water from the bottom kettle is added to make it a little more diluted. The tea is very strong so filling it half with the tea and the remained the hot water is typical. The glasses will be exceptionally hot, so must be held by the top rim only.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Turkish Teas Role in Turkish Culture</h2>\nTea is enjoyed from morning to evening in Turkey. It is also consumed at home as well as at coffeehouses throughout the country. It is a social drink and a method of showing hospitality. It is considered rude for any host to not allow their guest to drink as much of the popular beverage as they like.\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=35ae796a-8781-46d6-b7a0-18262f2948d8\" /></a></div>", "A Guide to Turkish Tea", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "a-guide-to-turkish-tea", "", "", "2013-12-09 16:57:43", "2013-12-09 16:57:43", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1370", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("1446", "2", "2013-12-09 16:54:52", "2013-12-09 16:54:52", "<article id=\"document_4418639\">\n<h1></h1>\n<div>\n\nNew York City has been the center of some of the greatest musical innovations of the modern era. From Broadway to the streets of Greenwich Village, music has had its home here. Jazz in particular found room to flourish in the Big Apple, with some of the greatest talents in the genre having been based there.\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>The Dorsey Brothers</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/19219926@N04/4032881660\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Dorsey Brothers at Duke, undated\" alt=\"Dorsey Brothers at Duke, undated\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2608/4032881660_ddbee8018b_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"153\" /></a>\n\nDespite not being from New York, the Dorsey Brothers were powerful forces in the jazz scene, specifically in the Big Band era. Like most jazz, Big Band started as a primarily African American sound, coming largely out of Harlem. The Dorseys were born andraised in Shenandoah, Pennsylvania where they learned a variety of instruments, with Jimmy focusing largely on woodwinds and B flat tuned instruments, becoming most famous for his clarinet and eventually trumpet work. Tommy, on the other hand, was more of a brass player, and was known primarily for his trombone playing.\n\nAgain, like many musical traditions of the time, Big Band\'s roots in the black communities had a limited reach outside of the community it started in. The Dorseys, being white musicians, managed to mainstream that music into a wider audience and their orchestras were among the first ever to be broadcast on radio stations at the time. They worked together and separately for a number of years, inspiring later greats likeColeman Hawkins and Lester Young, and their CBS variety program, Stage Show, was the first to broadcast Elvis Presley in the early 1950s.\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Miles Davis</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Miles_Davis_24.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured alignleft\" title=\"Miles Davis\" alt=\"Miles Davis\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Miles_Davis_24.jpg/300px-Miles_Davis_24.jpg\" width=\"270\" height=\"199\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMiles Davis was an aberration in jazz in general, especially New York jazz. The irony is that he invented a style that he never associated himself with.\n\nDavis was from a relatively affluent family from Alton, Illinois where he learned to play trumpet originally. His father gave him a trumpet at age 13 and arranged lessons with musician Elwood Buchanan, who was very deeply invested in the idea that music should be played without vibrato, preferring the clean, crisp sound that Davis was to replicate the rest of his life. He moved to New York to study at Julliard after high school where he discovered the wonders of bebop.\n\nBebop was raw, staccato, and right up Davis\'s alley, so much so that he considered himself a bebop player throughout his career. That\'s somewhat ironic, since he took the lessons from Buchanan and developed smooth jazz, a style that took off more on the West Coast but endeared him to mainstream listeners, giving him the clout and popularity of a rock and roll star well into the 60s after most jazz had fallen out of vogue. He was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2006 for his contributions to music.\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>John Coltrane</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.last.fm/music/John%2BColtrane\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"John Coltrane\" alt=\"John Coltrane\" src=\"http://userserve-ak.last.fm/serve/126/603812.jpg\" width=\"126\" /></a>\n\nJohn Coltrane was at the forefront of the free jazz movement that started and had it\'s popularity throughout the 1950s and early 60s. From a middle class North Carolina family that died almost all at once in his youth, Coltrane was raised by his mother and older cousin for most of his life. While he was a saxophonist for many years and even played in the Navy jazz band while he was enlisted, he really fell in love with the genre after hearing Charlie Parker play in 1945.\n\nTrane was known primarily for his versatility, able to adapt and replicate styles with ease. It\'s one of the reasons why he was so instrumental in the popularization of a number of different jazz modes during his career and organized countless recording sessions with famous artists of various genres. As his career progressed, his music became more spiritual in nature, and he was eventually canonized by the African Orthodox Church after his death in 1967.\n\nThe New York jazz scene was a peculiar one. It seems as if many of the greats started elsewhere, but it was New York City that gave them the fertile ground in which to grow their amazing talent and change the shape of music forever.\n\n</div>\n</article>\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=d1b82d4b-38bf-4fcc-9cfa-30effef5e1ba\" /></a></div>", "New York Citys Greatest Jazz Musicians", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "new-york-citys-greatest-jazz-musicians", "", "", "2013-12-09 16:54:52", "2013-12-09 16:54:52", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1446", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_3_posts` VALUES("1497", "2", "2013-12-09 16:50:34", "2013-12-09 16:50:34", "&nbsp;\n<div>\n<div>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe holiday season is a great time for giving to those less fortunate. Donating to a charity during the Christmas season can be a rewarding and gratifying experience. Helping out those in need during the holidays can offer a sense of joy and fulfillment. Many families struggle during this season and charities help families that need it more than others. It is important to add that the true nature of the holiday season involves giving to those in need. Below is a list of the top 4 holiday charities.\n<h2>Holiday Charity #1</h2>\n<em>Make-A-Wish Foundation</em>\nThis foundation grants the wishes of children that have been diagnosed with life-threatening health conditions. The Make-a-Wish Foundation not only grants the Christmas wishes of children, but the foundation helps wishes come true for children throughout the entire year. Donate to this charity during the holiday season to help grant the wish of a child that may not experience another holiday season. Make-A-Wish helps put a smile on children faces that are aged 2 to 18 years old. The Make-A-Wish Foundation is one of the worlds most important charities and has been granting holiday joy for many years.\n<h2>Holiday Charity #2</h2>\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/39247913@N06/8164226600\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Angel Tree_6\" alt=\"Angel Tree_6\" src=\"http://farm9.static.flickr.com/8478/8164226600_b92a365fb6_m.jpg\" width=\"161\" height=\"240\" /></a>\n\n<em>Angel Tree</em>\nThe Angel Tree is a charity provided through the Salvation Army. This charity offers new toys, clothes, and other gifts to less fortunate children for Christmas. Angel Tree places paper angels on Christmas trees throughout retail stores, malls, and other shopping locations. The paper angel has the gender, the first name, and the age of the child. Anyone can select one or more of the angels off the tree and buy age appropriate clothes, toys, or other gifts for the child. After purchasing the gifts, the gifts are returned to the place where the angels tree was selected. The parents can then pick up the gifts and take them home for Christmas.\n<h2>Christmas Charity #3</h2>\n<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:US_Navy_101201-N-2143T-002_Pfc._Eric_Tanis_puts_toys_in_a_collection_box_to_support_the_Marine_Toys_for_Tots_foundation.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured alignleft\" title=\"SILVERDALE, Wash. (Dec. 1, 2010) Pfc. Eric Tan...\" alt=\"SILVERDALE, Wash. (Dec. 1, 2010) Pfc. Eric Tan...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/US_Navy_101201-N-2143T-002_Pfc._Eric_Tanis_puts_toys_in_a_collection_box_to_support_the_Marine_Toys_for_Tots_foundation.jpg/300px-US_Navy_101201-N-2143T-002_Pfc._Eric_Tanis_puts_toys_in_a_collection_box_to_support_the_Marine_Toys_for_Tots_foundation.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"159\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Toys for Tots</em>\nDonating to Toys for Tots is probably one of the more convenient ways to help disadvantaged children during the Christmas season. This charity accepts brand new toys and distributes them to less fortunate families. The Toys for Tots campaign is one of the more popular charities and is conducted each year during the months of October, November, and December. Toys for Tots is a charity that helps children, who may not have had the opportunity, experience the joy of Christmas. Toys for Tots accepts donations anywhere a Marine Corps Reserve Unit can be found.\n<h2>Christmas Charity-#4</h2>\n<em>Samaritan\'s Purse: Operation Christmas Child</em>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/22693746@N03/3846471284\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Delivering Boxes\" alt=\"Delivering Boxes\" src=\"http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3489/3846471284_77226e8f84_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"185\" /></a>\n\nAlthough The Samaritans Purse is not as popular as many other charities; this charity brings joy to millions of children on Christmas. The Samaritan\'s Purse is a charity that provides shoe boxes filled with toys and other gifts to less fortunate children in different countries. The charity has a website that offers details on where to drop off the box, what to include in the shoe box, and how to pack it. Samaritans Purse has provided more than 100 million shoe box gifts to needy children since 1993.\nThe Christmas season is the perfect time to make donations and become involved with charities. Helping those in need offers a feeling that is unmatched. Donating gifts and being charitable is a selfless act of kindness that expresses the true nature of the Christmas holiday. Currently, there are thousands of foundations nationally and locally that offer Christmas joy to the less fortunate. It is important to add that making donations and offering personal time not only makes others feel better, but it can provide a sense of happiness and fulfillment.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=b2aab827-1724-4546-bc99-bebca15aee82\" /></a></div>", "Charities That Offer Something Special for the Holidays", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "charities-that-offer-something-special-for-the-holida", "", "", "2013-12-09 16:50:34", "2013-12-09 16:50:34", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1497", "0", "post", "", "0");
