INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1067", "2", "2013-09-23 13:46:29", "2013-09-23 13:46:29", "<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Cheese or paynir, as it is called in Turkey has been an important part of every Turkish meal for centuries. Varied ranges of cheese are produced in different regions of Turkey, and each has its own unique flavor and taste. The cheese is classified according to the type of milk and the animal from which the milk is obtained. Turkish cheese is processed from pasteurized, unpasteurized, raw and skimmed milk. The milk of cow, sheep, goat, buffalo, horse and camel have been used for centuries to process some of the best cheese the world has tasted. In modern day Turkey, the tastiest cheeses are processed from sheeps milk, but cows milk is usually used to produce cheese in Turkey.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">While some varieties are sold only in the areas in which they are prepared, others are sold in supermarkets all over Turkey. The locally processed cheese available in the local markets are fresh, delicious, healthy and exclusive. The processing secrets of the different cheese varieties are handed down from generation to generation and are much sought after by locals and visitors.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A major part of the milk produced in the country is used for cheese production. It is a must with every breakfast and used to prepare numerous dishes eaten for lunch and dinner. It is also eaten with fruits, used for dessert preparations and to prepare appetizers.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">There are more than 30 different kinds of cheese in Turkey. Here are some of the most famous ones:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>White cheese or beyaz paynir</strong> is prepared from cow or sheep milk. This cheese is curdled with Rennet and salted in brine and is mostly eaten for breakfast. It is an important ingredient in the traditional Turkish drink raki. It is also used to prepare omelets and macaroni dishes. It is also used to prepare the most famous national dish borek.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Kaar cheese</strong> is also processed from cow or sheep milk. Kasar processed from sheep milk is widely used in the Thracian region. This milk is curdled with Rennet, strained and boiled in brine water. The boiled cheese is poured in round shaped moulds. It is allowed to age. The outer part dries to form a crust. Cow or sheep milk kasar is eaten for breakfast. This cheese is also used in sandwiches and on baked delicacies.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Tulum cheese</strong> is made by placing the salted curd in cloth sacks or goatskins for 3 to 6 months. This tasty cheese is used to make borek and other such foods and is also used to prepare appetizers. Tulum tastes great when mixed with walnuts.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Mihalic (Kelle) cheese</strong> is produced like white cheese. It has big holes, a very salty flavor and is eaten with tea during breakfast.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Dil cheese</strong> looks like mozzarella and is similar to kasar cheese. While kasar is put in moulds, the curd for this cheese is stretched while boiling to give it a fibrous look. It too is eaten at breakfast. The cheese is either braided or packed in molds. The former, called Orgu meaning braid, is eaten cooked, and the latter is sold as Cerkez cheese.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Civil (Tel) cheese</strong> is a cheese variety that is kept in brine. It is widely produced in Eastern Anatolia and in areas near the Black Sea. Processed from non-fat cow\'s or goat\'s milk, it is eaten after being cooked in butter.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Local herbs are mixed in <strong>Van Otlu cheese</strong> to give it a unique taste and flavor. It is produced in Van, and its texture is similar to white cheese.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Lor cheese</strong> is used to prepare borek. Widely used during breakfast, it is mixed with various herbs and spices to prepare tasty appetizers.</p>\n\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=cd6bf69c-b647-4cb7-bf9c-5b5bf9b14df3\" /></a></div>", "Major Turkish Cheeses", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "major-turkish-cheeses", "", "", "2013-09-23 13:46:29", "2013-09-23 13:46:29", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1067", "0", "post", "", "0");
