INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1090", "2", "2013-09-25 14:18:51", "2013-09-25 14:18:51", "<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Mezes (meaning taste or snack) are mostly served as appetizers in Turkish restaurants, though they can serve as a light meal. There are a surprising amount of vegetarian and vegan mezes available. In a traditional Turkish restaurant, a waiter will come to your table with a tray that has all the mezes available. Customers choose one or two mezes each and they are placed in the center of the table to be shared communally. Ranging from dips eaten with bits of toasted flat-bread to salad-like dishes, there are mezes to suit every set of taste-buds.</p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Cacik (A chilled cucumber and yoghurt dip)</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"120\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cacik.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Cack is a popular soup-like food in Turkish c...\" alt=\"Cack is a popular soup-like food in Turkish c...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Cacik.jpg/300px-Cacik.jpg\" width=\"120\" /></a> Cack served with olive oil and dill.[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Made with tart seasoned yoghurt, cacik incorporates the taste of finely chopped cucumber and garlic with fresh mint and dill. It is often diluted with lime juice and olive oil to a dip-like consistency and garnished with sumac. It is served cold and eaten with toasted flat-bread.</p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\"></h2>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\"></h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Muhammara (A red pepper and walnut dip)</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"120\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Muhammara.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"English: Muhammara\" alt=\"English: Muhammara\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Muhammara.jpg/300px-Muhammara.jpg\" width=\"120\" /></a> Muhammara[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A favorite of many, this dip has a slightly spicy flavor. It\'s made using roasted red bell peppers and finely chopped walnuts. It is seasoned with garlic, cumin, hot red pepper flakes and salt. They use lemon juice, pomegranate molasses and fresh bread crumbs to make a dip like consistency that is usually eaten using toasted flat-bread.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Dolma (Grape leaves wrapped around a filling)</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"120\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sarma.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Sarma; a kind of dolma. It is a classic of Tur...\" alt=\"Sarma; a kind of dolma. It is a classic of Tur...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Sarma.jpg/300px-Sarma.jpg\" width=\"120\" /></a> Dolma[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">There are two types of dolmas in Turkey, one containing a meat mixture and one that is filled with a rice mixture. The vegetarian dolma is filled with rice, olive oil, currants (or sometimes dried figs or cherries), pinenuts, fresh herbs (such as dill, parsley, and mint), and spices (like black pepper, cinnamon, and allspice). They\'re usually served at room temperature with a lemon sauce. They\'re rolled somewhat similarly to an egg-roll but rolled in grape leaves rather than a wonton wrapper.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Saksuka (Fried eggplant with tomato sauce)</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"120\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Saksuka.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"English: Turkish Cuisine - Saksuka Trke: Tr...\" alt=\"English: Turkish Cuisine - Saksuka Trke: Tr...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Saksuka.jpg/300px-Saksuka.jpg\" width=\"120\" /></a> Saksuka[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">This tasty dish is composed of cubed and fried eggplant covered in a tomato sauce (tomato, sauted garlic, salt, and olive oil). In some places, green peppers and friend zucchini are added. It is usually served chilled with a dollop of yoghurt in the center and eaten with flat-bread.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Patates salatasi (Turkish potato salad)</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><a href=\"http://pera.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/patates-salatasi.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-1110 alignright\" alt=\"patates-salatasi\" src=\"http://pera.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/patates-salatasi-300x225.jpg\" width=\"126\" height=\"95\" /></a>This dish bears only a passing resemblance to its American cousin. It is a colorful and aromatic dish containing potatoes, black or green olives, roasted red bell pepper, feta cheese, garlic, onion, lemon juice and spices (cumin and oregano). It is served chilled.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify\">Zeytinyagli enginar (Stuffed artichokes)</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><a href=\"http://pera.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/zeytinyagli-enginar.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-1109 alignright\" alt=\"zeytinyagli-enginar\" src=\"http://pera.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/zeytinyagli-enginar-300x200.jpg\" width=\"126\" height=\"84\" /></a>Artichoke hearts cooked in olive oil with carrots, peas, onion and a bit of lemon juice. Sometimes fava beans and/or potatoes are included. It is served cold with a garnish of dill.</p>\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">These are but a small sampling of the wonderful vegetarian and vegan meze selections you can find. Many kinds of mixed vegetables and fruit dishes in addition to the ones listed above. Some meze are served hot, while others are served chilled or room temperature. The beauty of mezes is that you can try many different ones at one meal. Indeed, Mezes are a wonderful way to socialize during dinner as they encourage sharing and contact between diners.</p>", "Vegetarian Mezes of Turkey", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "vegetarian-mezes-of-turkey", "", "", "2013-09-25 14:18:51", "2013-09-25 14:18:51", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1090", "0", "post", "", "0");
