INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1147", "2", "2013-10-25 16:16:28", "2013-10-25 16:16:28", "Depending on the region in which a person lives, the staples in a Turk\'s diet may vary, but some ingredients are steeped in tradition and transcend geographical hindrance. Lamb is one of the most popular and widely used meats in Turkish cuisine, a cuisine that has been honed and perfected by professional chefs and home chefs alike.\n\nIn Turkish cooking, lamb has been common since the days when Turks were mostly nomadic tribes. Lamb and goat were available and transportable food sources, therefore they became a main focus of the Turkish diet. The tradition of lamb based meals has since passed down through the generations to continue to be served today.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Yeni2.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"English: Adana Kebab\" alt=\"English: Adana Kebab\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Yeni2.jpg/300px-Yeni2.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Adana Kebab[/caption]\n\nThere are several popular preparations for lamb. Adana style kebabs are named for the city in which they were created. The lamb (usually the hind and tail) is minced or ground, spiced with cumin, coriander, and sumac, shaped into patties and grilled on a 3-foot long skewer over hot coals. This preparation usually results in a spicy dish but can be modified as necessary.\n\nLamb Kofte is lamb meatballs made with spiced meat that has been minced or ground and rolled into balls that are then slightly flattened, skewered and grilled. These are often served with a curried yogurt.\n\nThe shish kebab is a well-known dish in Turkish cooking. The cut of lamb used is important so the meat is tender once cooked. Expensive cuts can drain the bank account but less expensive cuts will require time and patience to attain an acceptable cut for the kebab. Regardless of the price of the meat or labor involved in preparing the meat, if cooked well, the shish kebab should result in a tender bite. The recipe for a good kebab begins with the marinade for the meat. The marinade traditionally borrows from others cultures (Greek, Middle Eastern, and Indian are the most popular). The marinade, however, should not overpower the flavor of the meat. Turkish cuisine tends to allow the meat to shine, not to mask it\'s natural taste.\n\nAfter marinating the meat for a few hours the kebabs are assembled, sometimes with vegetables, and grilled over coals to add an element of smokiness. The meat still continues to be the star of the dish while served with a side of marinated vegetables.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shashlik_before_Grilling.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"English: Shashlik\" alt=\"English: Shashlik\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Shashlik_before_Grilling.JPG/300px-Shashlik_before_Grilling.JPG\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Shashlik[/caption]\n\nShashlik is another preparation popular in Turkish cooking. This kebab, however, was borrowed from the Russians. The lamb cubes (or slices) are marinated in a multi-dimensional marinade, which exhibits sweet, savory and at times even sour characteristics simultaneously, mixed with dairy and onions before being threaded on skewers and then grilled. Shashlik is a popular food sold by street vendors and is identified by it\'s sweet and sour flavors.\n\nAlthough the same protein is used, there are a myriad of ways to prepare the meat and any number of different flavors that can be infused in Turkish cuisine. Turkey proudly borrows from it\'s neighbors and incorporates new flavors into their own traditional food to enhance and differentiate taste. Any of the preparations discussed can be made right at home and are worth a try to experience to flavors of Turkey and the versatility of lamb.\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"></div>", "How To Cook Lamb Turkish Style", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "how-to-cook-lamb-turkish-style", "", "", "2013-10-25 16:16:28", "2013-10-25 16:16:28", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1147", "0", "post", "", "0");
