INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1265", "2", "2013-11-14 19:30:01", "2013-11-14 19:30:01", "Popular in Turkey and the Balkan countries is an unsweetened apritif, strong in alcohol with the flavorful bite of anise. Turkish Raki is the national alcoholic beverage of Turkey. The Turkish drink is frequently consumed straight though sometimes it is accompanied with chilled water. When water is added to the drink, as opposed to used as a chaser, the raki will turn a milky-white, thus earning the moniker lions milk.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>How Raki is Made</h2>\nTurkeys national beverage is traditionally distilled from the residue of grapes after winemaking. However, raisins and dried fruits do just as well, with their flavors carrying into the drink. Once the raisins, red wine leftovers, or fruits are done fermenting, anise seeds are put into the mix to bring out anethole, the essential oil of anise. A touch of sugar is then added and the entire mixture diluted down to 50%, bottled, and allowed to rest for 20 to 120 days. Aging isnt required with this elixir.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>What Raki Is Consumed With</h2>\nRaki is typically enjoyed with fish, especially mullet and mackerel, and with various mezes, or small dishes similar to tapas and unique to the Middle East and the Balkans. Some mezes that go well with Turkish raki are roasted chickpeas, freshly salted almonds, dolmas (stuffed grape leaves), hummus, and babaghanoush.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>History</h2>\nThough the Turks first introduced raki in the 1700s, for most of the Ottoman Empire, whose roots go back into the 1300s, mezes were served with wine, and selectively so, due to religious restrictions. It wasnt until the more liberal Tanzimat period in the mid-1800s that raki became popular. Unlike modern raki, which almost always incorporates anise, raki in the mid-1800s may have been enjoyed straight, since importing alcohol or anise seeds from elsewhere may have been a challenge.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Customs</h2>\nRegardless, the customs surrounding raki drinking grew quickly and follow strong traditions. Some celebrations of raki might be 6-8 people while others, perhaps to mark a marriage, might call for 25 or more. Its important to choose carefully those you wish to drink with because its expected that everyone participate in the conversation. Raki can also be enjoyed in smaller groups to have more intimate discussion. Turkish elders suggest that the nature of the gathering will influence the effect that the raki has on the drinkers.\n\nDrinking raki is for all ages and social classes. At a raki gathering, raki should be the only drink served. During toasts, the bottoms of the glasses are clinked together; touching the tops of the glass is a sign of arrogance. After the toast, the glass can be knocked lightly on the table in remembrance of those whom you wish were there.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Turkish Raki versus similar drinks</h2>\nTurkish raki is specifically different than the wide variety of non-anise-flavored brandies that are also popular in the Balkans and Southern Europe. Raki can refer to the Bulgarian rakia, the Greek tsipouro, and the Cypriot zivania, among other Balkan drinks. Raki in general indicates an alcoholic beverage distilled from pomace, or the residue from winemaking, but Turkish raki is differentiated by its incorporation of anise.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nFor a drink of only a few hundred years, Turkish raki has become a beloved apritif known far beyond Anatolia.\n\n&nbsp;\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=79cefa8e-f8c3-480f-bd32-593f8f51afd0\" /></a></div>", "Turkish Raki", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "turkish-raki", "", "", "2013-11-14 19:30:01", "2013-11-14 19:30:01", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1265", "0", "post", "", "0");
