INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1275", "2", "2013-11-14 21:17:23", "2013-11-14 21:17:23", "Istanbul is an ancient and modern city that is a perfect mix of cultures and traditions. The region offers much to see and do with the sites in the metropolis and the famous waters of the Bosporus for boating tours. A fabulous location for city breaks, travelers can stay near the old city (Sultanahmet) and walk almost anywhere they want to go. Here are five unique things to do in Istanbul:\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Admire the Rustem Pasha Mosque</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Suleymaniye_Mosques.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"Suleymaniye Mosque and Rustem Pasha Mosque\" alt=\"Suleymaniye Mosque and Rustem Pasha Mosque\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Suleymaniye_Mosques.JPG/300px-Suleymaniye_Mosques.JPG\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Suleymaniye Mosque and Rustem Pasha Mosque (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\nAn exquisite and small mosque, this structure built in honor of Rustem Pasha in 1561 is tall and seen for miles. Located just up the bank from the Bosporus and the bridge over the golden horn, this building is like a palace with more intricate blue tiles than any other building or mosque in the region. A slow touring is needed to fully appreciate the ornate beauty of the architecture. The atmosphere inside is peaceful, and the place is free from the large tourist crowds, an excellent spot to take a quiet few moments.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Browse the Istanbul Archaeology Museum</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dsc02722_istanbul_archaeology_museum_nevit.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"Image from Istanbul Archaeology Museum.\" alt=\"Image from Istanbul Archaeology Museum.\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Dsc02722_istanbul_archaeology_museum_nevit.jpg/300px-Dsc02722_istanbul_archaeology_museum_nevit.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Image from Istanbul Archaeology Museum. (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\nFirst opened to the public in the 1890s, this museum has one of the largest collections of ancient artifacts, well over a million. Here are found treasures from the past, from the Egyptian, Greco-Roman and Byzantine eras. Besides the majestic sarcophagus of Alexander, the complex holds many other wonders of years past. An entire section is dedicated to the Orient. Taking time to explore the various sections and buildings in the complex is worthwhile to become saturated with the stories and objects from ancient times.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Cruise the Bosporus</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"240\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/76261353@N00/5834161\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"Bosphorus\" alt=\"Bosphorus\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/4/5834161_9f08c9dc43_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a> Bosphorus (Photo credit: bayat)[/caption]\n\nAmazing views of the Asian and European banks as well as the sunlight or city lights at night sparkling on the waters await those who choose to cruise the Bosporus. This body of water links two continents together and holds a rich history. Taking a ferry is the least-expensive option for the trip. The ride offers much to see during the day and at night, and the trip up the Bosporus and back to the dock lasts about six hours.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Explore the Basilica Cistern</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"200\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Basilica_Cistern.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"English: The entrance to the Basilica Cistern ...\" alt=\"English: The entrance to the Basilica Cistern ...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Basilica_Cistern.jpg/300px-Basilica_Cistern.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /></a> English: The entrance to the Basilica Cistern in Istanbul, Turkey. (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\nRight across from the Blue Mosque (Sultanahmet Mosque), this fascinating underground cistern was constructed in the mid-500s by the Romans. The structure includes stately pillars and other ornate architectural details typical of Rome. Because of the various styles of filigree, the recycling of columns for use at the cistern is obvious. The columns appear gathered from various temples and governmental buildings. Some visitors choose to come early in the day to avoid the long lines that are necessary later.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Play at Babalu Park</h2>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"180\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/44124401641@N01/1794835167\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"combover\" alt=\"combover\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2289/1794835167_91021136c5_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" /></a> Fun in Babalu Park[/caption]\n\nA fantastic activity park for families with children between the ages of four and twelve, this park encourages active play with little cars for children to drive and plenty of safe equipment on which they can climb. The indoor playground is the perfect place to play on rainy and snowy days. The facility offers dining and tasty food for hungry people old and young. Babalu Park is also ideal for children\'s birthday parties, and babysitting is available.\n\n&nbsp;\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=c846a1aa-4833-4014-a348-c3533647d1f0\" /></a></div>", "5 Unique Things to Do in Istanbul", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "5-unique-things-to-do-in-istanbul", "", "", "2013-11-14 21:17:23", "2013-11-14 21:17:23", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1275", "0", "post", "", "0");
