INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1533", "2", "2013-05-12 12:00:28", "2013-05-12 12:00:28", "Turkey is a gorgeous country with an eclectic mix of cultures, styles, foods, and ethnicities. If you have been thinking of a vacation to the Mediterranean then be sure to add Turkey to your destination list. The cities located on the sea are beautiful paradises with much to do and the rest of the country has amazing sights and destinations as well.\n\nIn this article we will discuss three items that will help you plan your trip to Turkey:\n<ul>\n	<li>Money</li>\n	<li>Culture</li>\n	<li>Food</li>\n</ul>\n<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:5000_TL_obverse.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"English: 5000 Turkish Lira Obverse (1st versio...\" alt=\"English: 5000 Turkish Lira Obverse (1st versio...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/5000_TL_obverse.jpg/300px-5000_TL_obverse.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"153\" /></a>\n<h1><b>Money: Getting It and Spending It</b></h1>\nThe currency in Turkey is the Turkish Lira (TL), which is split into 100 kurus (kr).\n\nYou can change money at your local bank, international airports, international banks, or currency change shops around larger cities in Turkey. Try to ensure youre getting a fair exchange rate by doing your research ahead of time. Use cash instead of credit cards whenever possible. It is common to use the Euro at some shops, restaurants and other locations. Sometimes, US dollars may be accepted as well, but local currency is best.\n\nMany cities in Turkey have bazaars and local shops. Bargaining is part of the culture. You can usually expect to have great service from shop owners. They will answer questions. Make sure you are clear about your intentions. You dont want to lead any shop owner into thinking you are purchasing only to leave with nothing.\n\nTurkey is known for excellent leather goods, castile soaps and pottery along with many great foods and drinks. Youll be able to find that leather vest or business bag youve always wanted cheaper than anywhere else. Silk is also something youll want to haggle over and bring home with you. Scarves and dresses in any color you can imagine are available from vendors all over Turkey, especially Bursa. Be careful when buying antiques or food items. Going through customs may prove to be tricky.\n<h1><b>Culture: Things to Look For</b></h1>\nTurkey has an eclectic mix of cultures. The culture is based on respect and honor. Elders are highly regarded, so give up your bus seat to the old lady that boards after you. If you show respect and use manners during your visit in Turkey you will find the people to be welcoming and generous.\n\nBring a gift if invited to the home of a Turkish native. Flowers, desserts and sweets (especially Turkish Delight) are welcomed. Turkish natives are excellent hosts so there wont be any need to ask for anything. Enjoy your time immersed in their culture.\n\nThe most widely followed sport in Turkey isfootball (soccer). Volleyball (especially women\'s) has also been an up and comer, with many team and national level international successes in recent years. You can usually find a local event in larger cities where people gather to cheer and celebrate.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"130\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Food_fromTurkey.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Dolma, Baklava, Gzleme, Pilav, Fincan-brei,...\" alt=\"Dolma, Baklava, Gzleme, Pilav, Fincan-brei,...\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Food_fromTurkey.jpg/300px-Food_fromTurkey.jpg\" width=\"130\" /></a> Dolma, Baklava, Gzleme, Pilav, Fincan-brei, Sarma, Borek[/caption]\n<h1><b>Food: Tastes of Turkey</b></h1>\nTurkish cuisine is rich and carries influences from Mediterranean, Asian, and Arabic countries.\n\nThe most common protein youll find is beef followed by lamb, both of which will be richly flavored and served accompanied by local vegetables. Eggplants, lentils, onions, beans, tomatoes, and garlic are the vegetables youll most often find in Turkish dishes. Finding a purely vegetarian dish might be difficult depending on the region youre in but they are available.\n\nYou may be familiar with a Turkish staple called kebabs, which are chunks of meat and vegetables skewered and grilled and served with sauces and sometimes rice. Kebabs are one of the many specialties in Turkey.\n\nTurkish desserts are often nutty and sweetened with honey. Baklava can be found abundantly including pastries, nuts, honey, and spices combine to make this unique confection. Milk-based desserts like puddings are also common. Try a few different things and see what you like best!.\n\nBe sure to try a Turkish coffee while youre there and youll never feel the same about coffee again.\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"></div>", "A Guide to Traveling in Turkey", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "a-guide-to-traveling-in-turkey", "", "", "2013-05-12 12:00:28", "2013-05-12 12:00:28", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=198", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1534", "2", "2013-05-16 12:00:12", "2013-05-16 12:00:12", "Traditional Turkish cuisine is rich in flavors, colors, and heritage. There are many cultures that have influenced the food now found in Turkey. The wines that complement these dishes are made from some of the grape varieties indigenous to the many regions of Turkey. The unique flavors have something that will surely please everyone.\n<h1><b>Meat and Vegetable Dishes</b></h1>\nLamb is common in Turkey. Its incorporated in many traditional dishes. An example of a traditional dish is Karnyark, which is a savory dish made with eggplant, minced lamb, onions, garlic, tomato filling, and fresh parsley. It is often served over rice.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"130\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/36521977367@N01/2538897504\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Lahmacun\" alt=\"Lahmacun\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2116/2538897504_3690c8dbd0_m.jpg\" width=\"130\" /></a> Lahmacun[/caption]\n\nAnother dish that uses both meat and vegetables is Lahmacun, which resembles pizza in some ways. With Syrian roots, this dish is richly spiced minced lamb with onions on a flaky dough crust. It can be eaten just like pizza or it can be rolled and eaten more like a taco. It is typically served with lettuce, tomatoes, and parsley. You will often see people squirt fresh lemon juice on it as well. Try this with a rich merlot, which often comes from the Marmara region in Turkey.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h1><b>Vegetarian Dishes</b></h1>\nDishes that are purely vegetarian are referred to as zeytin yal which means cooked with olive oil and are generally served cold. With a nod to a traditional Greek dish, Yaprak Sarma is vine leaves wrapped around a filling of rice, onion, mint, and other spices. They are a rich deep green that would match well with a Sauvignon Blanc which is mostly commonly crafted in the Aegean region of Turkey.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"140\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/10559879@N00/4449090451\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Spinach Borek - insides - Brew Bar AUD10\" alt=\"Spinach Borek - insides - Brew Bar AUD10\" src=\"http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4050/4449090451_43cf1a5d34_m.jpg\" width=\"140\" /></a> Borek[/caption]\n\nIf your palette calls for something with a pastry essence, try any variety of Borek. It is pastry dough either stuffed with savory filling or layered and cooked. It is sometimes filled with beef but most restaurants offer a vegetarian option as well. They are often stuffed with spinach, cheeses, or at a place with a more eclectic chef, eggplant. If you choose to pair this with wine, opt for a lighter, sweeter white like a Riesling. You could also opt for the traditional Turkish drink raki.\n<h1><b>Wine and Other Drinks</b></h1>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"100\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/62963259@N05/8389432671\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Raki by the fire\" alt=\"Raki by the fire\" src=\"http://farm9.static.flickr.com/8356/8389432671_282e3ff976.jpg\" width=\"100\" /></a> Raki by the fire[/caption]\n\nRaki is a traditional and widely available drink of Turkey. It is served straight or with chilled water, depending on your preference. Due to its milky white color when mixed with water, is it often called aslan st which means lions milk The liquor is anise flavored and is known as the national drink of Turkey. If you prefer wine over liquor, there are many options to choose from.\n\nNearly 1200 different types of grapes grow indigenous in Turkish soil though only about 100 are harvested for wine. You will find any type of wine you like has a vineyard that makes it in Turkey. Some Turkish wines are harvested and made in the ice wine fashion. The grapes are allowed to hang on the vine until the first frost. They are then harvested and crushed while still frozen. This makes for a sweeter, dessert wine.\n\nWith all the wonderful food and wine options available in Turkey, youre sure to experience a full range of flavors and never have to eat the same thing twice!\n\n&nbsp;\n<h6 class=\"zemanta-related-title\" style=\"font-size: 1em\">Related articles</h6>\n<ul class=\"zemanta-article-ul zemanta-article-ul-image\" style=\"margin: 0;padding: 0;overflow: hidden\">\n	<li class=\"zemanta-article-ul-li-image zemanta-article-ul-li\" style=\"padding: 0;background: none;float: left;vertical-align: top;text-align: left;width: 84px;font-size: 11px;margin: 2px 10px 10px 2px\"><a style=\"padding: 2px;text-decoration: none\" href=\"http://peranyc.com/blog/a-guide-to-traveling-in-turkey/\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"padding: 0;margin: 0;border: 0;width: 80px\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://i.zemanta.com/168221143_80_80.jpg\" /></a><a style=\"overflow: hidden;text-decoration: none;line-height: 12pt;height: 80px;padding: 5px 2px 0 2px\" href=\"http://peranyc.com/blog/a-guide-to-traveling-in-turkey/\" target=\"_blank\">A Guide to Traveling in Turkey</a></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=3cbc59b9-5447-4f07-a33b-336a4e49d94f\" /></a></div>", "Turkish Delight: Traditional Food and Wine of Turkey", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "traditional-food-and-wine-of-turkey", "", "", "2013-05-16 12:00:12", "2013-05-16 12:00:12", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=271", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1535", "2", "2013-05-20 12:00:10", "2013-05-20 12:00:10", "When planning your vacation in Turkey, there are many opportunities for fun and adventure. Consider the people youre traveling with, especially if you bring young children. Do you research on the places you want to go to beforehand- things may not be as accessible as youre used to.\n\nWhether youre an adventurer, a museum rat, an art critic, or an animal lover you will find something amazing to do in Turkey with everyone in your party.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/65037227@N00/142320294\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Bosphorus\" alt=\"Bosphorus\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/46/142320294_d6f42d5ede_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"192\" /></a> Bosphorus[/caption]\n\nIf you find yourself in Istanbul, a great way to see a few sites is a cruise of the Bosphorus Strait. Many companies offer shorter day cruises, night cruises, or dinner cruises. The Sumela Monastery in Trabzon should definitely make your list for the views, the history, and the sense of peace youll leave with. They have undergone construction so some of the building may not be accessible but the view alone is breathtaking. Check the weather before you go!\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"240\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/47096398@N08/5864767980\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Ephesus Museum, Turkey\" alt=\"Ephesus Museum, Turkey\" src=\"http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5182/5864767980_54c9971b40_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"169\" /></a> Ephesus Museum, Turkey[/caption]\n\nIf museums are more to your taste, you dont want to miss the Ephesus Museum in Selcuk. The ancient ruins of this well preserved historic city are located nearby the museum. The last 140 years of excavations have cultivated many artifacts that are now on display in the museum. The Istanbul Museum of Turkish and Islamic Art resides in the largest palace built under the Ottomans. Calligraphy, carpets, glassware, and Korans from all parts of the Islamic world are proudly displayed at this museum.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/87605170@N00/6392738255\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"No Pictures!\" alt=\"No Pictures!\" src=\"http://farm7.static.flickr.com/6115/6392738255_55a7c5ca9d_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"179\" /></a> Istanbul Modern Art Museum[/caption]\n\nIf art is more your style, the Istanbul Modern Art Museum houses pieces by Turkish artists as well as artists from around the globe. This is a family-friendly attraction that immerses you in the modern art world. The museum also boasts a cinema, design store, library, and restaurant. You could surely spend an entire day here. The Turkish and Islamic Art Museum is also located in Istanbul. It houses more traditional art pieces like tiles, rugs, and calligraphy. This is the place to go for a more historic art experience.\n\nIf you love marine life, Istanbul is a great place to visit. They boast a dolphinarium where you can see dolphin shows. They also have programs where you can swim with the dolphins or SCUBA dive with them! The largest indoor dolphin exhibit in Europe, the Istanbul Dolphinarium is a must-visit, especially if you are bringing along children!\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"240\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/96234041@N00/7241794486\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"LR-1040441\" alt=\"LR-1040441\" src=\"http://farm8.static.flickr.com/7075/7241794486_3afe8da6eb_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" /></a> Istanbul Aquarium[/caption]\n\nIt may be crowded but that only shows how popular the Istanbul Aquarium really is! With species from all over the world, youll see sharks, sting rays, and amazon fish. The mix of history, nature, and culture blends well to give you a full aquatic experience. Its far from the largest aquarium in the world but the large tanks and excellent variety of animals makes for a great experience.\n\nWith a little bit of planning and a taste for adventure, you will surely have a once in a lifetime experience in Turkey. As on any trip, check the weather, wear the right shoes, bring a bottle of water, and keep your belongings safe! And of course, take a lot of pictures!\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=0ac41582-f56f-4bbb-af74-2a7ea55af70b\" /></a></div>", "Things to Do In Turkey During Your Vacation", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "things-to-do-in-turkey-during-your-vacation", "", "", "2013-05-20 12:00:10", "2013-05-20 12:00:10", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=308", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1536", "2", "2013-12-09 16:49:25", "2013-12-09 16:49:25", "<p style=\"text-align: justify\">New York City is famous for its tall buildings, historic statue and food, but when the holiday season arrives, the city becomes famous for its dcor. Popular seasonal sites include Rockefeller Center and Times Square. In addition, the citys store windows are truly magnificent during the holidays. Specifically, stores like Macys, Tiffanys, Lord &amp; Taylor, Saks Fifth Avenue, and Bloomingdales create visual masterpieces in their windows.</p>\n\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Macys</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/70323761@N00/2061984223\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"NYC - Macy\'s 2007 Holiday Window Display - San...\" alt=\"NYC - Macy\'s 2007 Holiday Window Display - San...\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2269/2061984223_06a13fd0e4_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" /></a>\n\nMacys celebrates Thanksgiving and Christmas in a big way since the store presents one of the worlds most annual famous parades. For its holiday windows, the store includes two displays. Each year, Macys creates a window display that focuses on the Miracle on 34th Street film. The store also decorates a second set of windows in themes that change annually.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Tiffanys</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/11967895@N05/2077398259\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured alignleft\" title=\"Tiffany\'s 2007 Holiday Windows\" alt=\"Tiffany\'s 2007 Holiday Windows\" src=\"http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2142/2077398259_1b2549d28e_m.jpg\" width=\"146\" height=\"192\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The classic jewelry store, which is located on Fifth Avenue, is famous for decorating its windows in classic themes. This year, holiday shoppers can view scenes portraying Upper East Side apartments. Each scene features backgrounds in varying shades of blue. In addition, the display\'s holiday revelers are getting ready for Christmas by hanging stockings. Mom and Dadkiss underneath the mistletoe in one scene while the awe-inspiring sight of an enormous Christmas tree fills another store window.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Lord &amp; Taylor</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/15302609@N00/5188477277\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured \" title=\"lord and taylor holiday window\" alt=\"lord and taylor holiday window\" src=\"http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1027/5188477277_5bb30440d5_m.jpg\" width=\"216\" height=\"216\" /></a>\n\nFor the 2013 holiday season, the popular department store decorated its windows in a vintage design. The presentation includes holiday scenes with glamorous shoppers purchasing Christmas gifts at Lord &amp; Taylor as well as people walking through the citys streets. The stores holiday window display also features children visiting Santa and couples dancing. Shoppers will find Lord &amp; Taylor on Fifth Avenue at 39th Street.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Saks Fifth Avenue</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/84035351@N00/3158393102\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Saks Snowflakes\" alt=\"Saks Snowflakes\" src=\"http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3283/3158393102_5344390c74_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" /></a>\n\nSaks Fifth Avenue, which is located on 611 Fifth Avenue, usually chooses family-friendly displays. The stores holiday theme for this year is Snowflake Spectacular, and it includes a thrilling 3D light show on the buildings faade. In addition, the windows feature scenes depicting children playing in the snow. Saks dedicates six of its windows to each years holiday theme.    During the unveiling ceremony, the store typically provides entertainment by famous musicians and vocalists.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Bloomingdales</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/70323761@N00/3093556561\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"NYC: Bloomingdale\'s 2008 Holiday Window - A Sw...\" alt=\"NYC: Bloomingdale\'s 2008 Holiday Window - A Sw...\" src=\"http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3114/3093556561_a0cc816c20_m.jpg\" width=\"160\" height=\"240\" /></a>\n\nBloomingdales is located on Lexington Avenue, and when shoppers visit the department store this holiday season, theyll surely stop to view the holiday windows. Bloomingdales frequently presents classic themes. This year, the store created windows with various country themes from destinations like China, France and Italy. To display the different themes, the stores window designers added a big gift box to each window. The bottom of each box has a swiveling mechanism that turns to reveal the windows country. For instance, the Italy themed gift box features the tower of Pisa, ancient ruins and a gondola.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNew York City visitors and locals will surely find their holiday spirit when they spend a day viewing seasonal window displays. Each store features a unique theme and presentation to create excitement for the season. Imaginative store windows may also encourage people to step inside the store to begin their holiday shopping.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=b1fd4c35-3ce6-4e2a-a22c-46623f1cabd0\" /></a></div>", "Window Shopping, a NYC Holiday Tradition", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "window-shopping-a-nyc-holiday-tradition", "", "", "2013-12-09 16:49:25", "2013-12-09 16:49:25", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1295", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1558", "2", "2013-12-20 21:09:04", "2013-12-20 21:09:04", "Makes approximately 1 dozen kofta balls\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<em>2 Eggplants</em>\n<em> 4 oz parmesan cheese (crated)</em>\n<em> 8 oz panko (breadcrumbs)</em>\n<em>  clove of garlic (minced)</em>\n<em> Parsley (chop up a couple of stems)</em>\n\n<strong>Outside of Kofta</strong>\n\n<em>2 eggs</em>\n<em> 4 oz flour</em>\n<em> 4 oz breadcrumbs</em>\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"200\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/47696637@N03/6769358683\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Eggplant\" alt=\"Eggplant\" src=\"http://farm8.static.flickr.com/7035/6769358683_f679b8bef1_n.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a> Eggplant[/caption]\n\nPoke holes in eggplant and char them until blackened and tender. Remove skin and put eggplant in a strainer to remove juice.\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Take flesh of eggplant and chop it up finely. Add parmesan cheese, parsley, garlic and eggplant puree and breadcrumbs. Mix it all together.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Scoop 1 oz balls and roll in flour and then the beaten egg and finally the breadcrumbs.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Heat up 3 oz canola oil in pan on medium heat. Place rolls in the pan and cook until golden brown and delicious on all sides. Once cooked, remove from pan and let rest on paper towel and serve.</p>\nEnjoy.\n\nChef Gavin Citron\nPera Soho\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=e273c65f-d0af-4bc8-8b51-678490e7d8ed\" /></a></div>", "Eggplant Kofta Recipe", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "eggplant-kofta-recipe-2", "", "", "2013-12-20 21:09:04", "2013-12-20 21:09:04", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1558", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1560", "2", "2013-12-28 21:13:09", "2013-12-28 21:13:09", "<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Makes 20 rolls</strong></p>\n\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>INGREDIENTS</strong></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><em>20 Phyllo leaves</em> <em> 8 oz. feta cheese</em>\n<em> 1 egg (beaten)</em>\n<em> 3 stalks of dill (minced)</em>\n<em>  lb kasseri cheese (grated) can substitute with mozzarella</em></p>\n\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left\">DIRECTIONS</h3>\nEgg wash for roll  1 egg beaten\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"200\"]<a href=\"http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Feta_Greece_2.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Feta from Greece\" alt=\"Feta from Greece\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Feta_Greece_2.jpg/350px-Feta_Greece_2.jpg\" width=\"200\" /></a> Feta (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Mix feta cheese, beaten egg, dill, kasseri cheese in a bowl.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Take a phyllo leaf, lay it flat. Put 1 tsp of stuffing on the leaf. Begin rolling the leaf, fold in sides and continue rolling until a roll. Brush egg wash on roll.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">3 oz of canola oil in a pan. Heat oil on medium. Place phyllo roll in pan. Gently turn as they turn golden brown and delicious on each side. Once completely brown take out of pan and let rest on a paper towel.</p>\nCacik\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>INGREDIENTS FOR PHYLLO ROLLS<strong>SAUCE</strong></strong></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><em> cucumber (peeled, cored and minced)</em>\n<em> 3 oz yoghurt (plain)</em>\n<em> 1 stalk dill (finely chopped)</em>\n<em> 1/3 clove garlic (minced)</em>\n<em> Squeezed fresh lemon</em></p>\n\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left\">DIRECTIONS</h3>\nMix all of the above ingredients.\n\nServe on a platter with phyllo rolls and enjoy!\n\nChef Gavin Citron\nPera Soho\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=f98aada1-fbef-45f2-9572-17d06ff0a7c7\" /></a></div>", "Phyllo Rolls Recipe", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "phyllo-rolls-recipe-2", "", "", "2013-12-28 21:13:09", "2013-12-28 21:13:09", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1560", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("1574", "2", "2014-02-14 15:55:17", "2014-02-14 15:55:17", "<p style=\"text-align: justify\">As Turkey\'s economy has improved and prospered, European and American cultural influence has grown and mingled with its more traditional customs. More and more Turkish citizens are participating in \"western\" holidays, such as Christmas, New Year\'s, and Valentine\'s Day, albeit in a slightly different manner and in a more commercialized context. Valentine\'s Day, in particular, is relatively new to Turkey; it has only been recognized and celebrated for roughly 15-20 years. While the country is secular in nature, a large portion of its population is Islamic, and it might not resonate as strongly to celebrate a figure such as St. Valentine. Therefore, Valentine\'s Day is more commonly referred to as Lovers\' Day, or<i>Sevgililer Gn</i>. It is a romantic day set aside to honor one\'s spouse or significant other. Unlike most American traditions, in which valentines are extended to family and friends as well as lovers, the Turkish Lovers\' Day is a day for celebrating romantic relationships alone.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"220\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/43437461@N00/4353033901\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured\" title=\"Happy Valentine\'s Day...\" alt=\"Happy Valentine\'s Day...\" src=\"http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4019/4353033901_2f69b2c374_n.jpg\" width=\"220\" /></a> Happy Valentine\'s Day... (Photo credit: erry)[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">While the new traditions have spread to smaller towns and villages, most Valentine\'s Day festivities occur in the larger cities like Istanbul and Ankara. It is observed in Turkey largely the same as it is in America and other western countries. Malls and shopping centers are bedecked with red hearts and roses, parades march down the streets, and hotels and restaurants feature Valentine-themed specials and menus. Travel agencies are busy booking romantic getaways to showcase their beautiful country, while fashionable nightclubs host mixers and singles\' programs for the unattached. Some banks even extend special lines of holiday credit, just for Valentine\'s shopping. Young couples usually dine out for the evening and exchange small tokens of affection. Modest jewelry, perfume, flowers, and chocolates are popular gifts for women, while watches and cologne do for their suitors.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In the cities, it is usually the younger generation that embraces the holiday. In the outer regions, it is still taking some time for the acceptance of such western traditions. However, the old ways and the new are showing signs of merging. Here, Lovers\' Day recognizes and extols older, long-married couples, in a testament to their mutual faith and enduring love. Whether celebrated on Valentine\'s Day or Sevgililer Gn, love gets its due in Turkey as much as it does in the western world.</p>\n\n<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\" style=\"margin-top: 10px;height: 15px\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\"><img class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" style=\"border: none;float: right\" alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=b798c564-137f-4dd6-b9c3-5b359dd82ed4\" /></a></div>", "Valentine\'s Day in Turkey", "", "publish", "closed", "closed", "", "valentines-day-in-turkey", "", "", "2014-02-14 15:55:17", "2014-02-14 15:55:17", "", "0", "http://peranyc.com/blog/?p=1574", "0", "post", "", "0");
